---

In my last post, we talked about the three steps of enshittification
(the gradual process by which platforms like Facebook become shitty).

To recap, the three steps were:

1. Make a platform great for users
2. Start favouring business customers, making the platform worse for users
3. Make the platform worse for business customers by squeezing them dry

## There’s a fourth step — and we’re going to talk about it today

I joked last time that step 4 is simply *Die(?)*, but as we’ve all seen,
platforms don’t announce their deaths publicly, nor do they disappear quietly
into the night.

From what we can tell, after platforms have extracted as much as they can from
both users and business customers, they try to aggressively pivot — by trying to
take on the whole world.

## The Pivot

Take a look at Meta. Facebook’s organic reach has become unpredictable,
Instagram is a casino of Reels you didn’t ask for, the ad auction feels tapped
out, and small-business accounts get banned left, right, and centre. You could
argue the squeeze is complete.

So what did Zuck do? He didn’t fix the platforms for users or business
customers. Instead, he pivoted to the metaverse — a VR office nobody asked for.
When that flopped, he pivoted to AI, pushing chatbots, image generators, and
agents. And, just for good measure, he threw in some AR Ray-Ban glasses.
Anything but actually improve the experience on the social media platforms he
controls.

X (formerly Twitter) is even wilder. You can smell the stage-four desperation a
mile away. The user experience is terrible — unless you pay a monthly
subscription, your posts aren’t seen by anyone, and even when you do pay, it’s
still a lottery. Rage content runs rampant, and neuroticism is promoted so much
that advertisers have fled the platform. So what does Elon do? He tells everyone
he wants to turn X into an “everything app” — payments, video calls, job
listings, dating, shopping, a WeChat for the West, and, of course, Grok AI. He
openly talks about creating a new financial system on X, one you’ll never need
to leave.

## Why do they do this?

I don’t believe these people are inherently evil. I just believe — like everyone
else — they act on incentives. And their incentive is to make as much money as
possible for themselves and their shareholders.

The enshittification playbook has run to its logical end on these platforms.
They’ve squeezed all they can from the people who post content and the people
who pay to reach them. There’s no juice left in the orange. But because they’re
publicly traded companies, they can’t just say, “From now on, we’ll be a steady
cash cow.” They have to find new ways to squeeze, because the number must
always go up. There have to be new investors who believe in the company’s future
— so the old investors can sell their shares to someone. That’s the game.

Thus, the Everything App. Thus, the AI pivot. Thus, the metaverse. It’s all a
shiny new story to tell investors while the core product rots. The whole “we’re
building the future” line is a marketing tactic; what they’re really doing is
jumping ship.

## What this means for you and me

I’ve watched the enshittification process play out over and over again. One
minute a platform is a goldmine for a creator, and the next, nobody sees your
posts anymore — because the founder has decided the company is now “AI-first.”
The posts you made to help people end up being used to train an AI that might
replace you.

You can’t stop it. Enshittification is a one-way ratchet. The founders and early
employees got rich, users got a free party, advertisers got cheap clicks, and
now the whole machine is cannibalising itself looking for one more hit of
growth. The step-four “everything” pivot is just the death rattle in a Silicon
Valley slide deck.

That’s why I ended the last blog the way I did: **you don’t build on social
media anymore — you extract.** The point of your TikTok, your Instagram, your
Twitter account is not to be a loyal tenant in someone else’s crumbling
apartment complex. It’s to funnel people toward the place you actually own —
your newsletter, your blog, your self-hosted community. Somewhere that will
never wake up one morning and decide it’s an AI-powered payments super-app.

Step 4 of enshittification is the most dangerous phase because it’s coated in
promises of revolution. But if you know to watch for it, you can pack your bags
and leave before the roof caves in.
